                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-184-victim1526 t18300527-184-viclabel985"></join> - we live in <placeName id="t18300527-184-crimeloc986">Park-place</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-184-crimeloc986" type="placeName" value="Park-place"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-184-crimeloc986" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-184-off983 t18300527-184-crimeloc986"></join>. On the 27th of May I was speaking to a woman in my room; it rained, and she went down stairs with me - she asked me what time it was; I went up to see, and the watch was then safe - the prisoner was then in the room with my husband; he bade my husband good afternoon, and went away - when I went up again the watch was gone.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-184-person1529">
                  ROBERT 
                  CURRIE
               <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1529" type="surname" value="CURRIE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1529" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1529" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went to the prisoner's lodgings on the 28th of May, at No. 2, Meard's-court, Piccadilly; I asked the prisoner if his name was Maplestone - he said No; I said, "From your appearance I think you are the man I want;" he said, "What do you want" - I said, "You are charged with robbing a trumpeter of the 2nd Life Guards, of his watch;" he denied all knowledge of it - I said he must go down to the barracks; as soon as the prosecutrix saw him she said he was<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183005270085"></xptr>the man - I asked him if he had pawned any watch; he said No - I went towards a pawnbroker's, where the prosecutrix said she had heard a watch had been offered; the prisoner then asked if I would allow him to make it up -I said No, and said,"What have you done with it?" he said he had pawned it at a shop opposite the chapel, in Broadway, Westminster, which was Mr. Williams - he said afterwards that he denied his name because he was in debt.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-184-person1530">
                  JOHN 
                  WILLIAMS
               <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1530" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1530" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-184-person1530" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. This watch was pawned with me by the prisoner, on Thursday last - he said it was his own, and had been in the family many years.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. The prosecutor told me that if I would make it up, I might - the proof of pawning, is not a proof of taking it.</p>
